WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6.08 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6 minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Neil

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
And I'm Beth.

5
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:17.000
Neil, do you remember the children's television show, Lassie?

6
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Oh yes, of course. The show's hero was a dog named Lassie and Lassie went around helping people in trouble.

7
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Yes, well, if you watched Lassie as a child, you might also remember the TV shows

8
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:37.000
Flip of the dolphin and skipy the kangaroo. The stars of these shows were animals who would also come to the rescue of humans in trouble.

9
00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:42.000
In this program, we'll be discussing some real-life animals helping people in trouble.

10
00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:47.000
It might sound strange, but we'll be hearing how cows are helping to stop fires in Spain.

11
00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:52.000
Well, now I have a picture in my head of a cow wearing a fireman's helmet.

12
00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:54.000
But I guess that's not what you mean, Neil.

13
00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:59.000
Not quite Beth, but you're right about the fires or wildfires to be exact.

14
00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:05.000
Wildfires are unplanned fires in areas like forests or grasslands, which spread out of control.

15
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:08.000
They often happen in hot dry countries like Spain.

16
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:15.000
So how could cows help? We'll be finding out and learning some useful new vocabulary as well.

17
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:21.000
And remember, if you like to read along as you listen to the program, you'll find a script on our website.

18
00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:23.000
BBCLearningEnglish.com

19
00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:31.000
But now I have a question for you Beth. Some wildfires are caused naturally, but most are the result of human activity.

20
00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:38.000
So, according to the Natural History Museum of Utah, what proportion of wildfires is caused by people?

21
00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:45.000
Is it A, 2 out of every 5? B, 3 out of every 5? Or C, 4 out of every 5?

22
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:49.000
I'm going to guess 3 out of every 5, I think.

23
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:51.000
Let's find out at the end of the program.

24
00:01:52.000 --> 00:02:00.000
Thanks to increasing temperatures caused by climate change, the wildfires happening today are more intense and more destructive than ever before.

25
00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:13.000
Here, Craig Langran, reporter for BBC World Service program, People Fixing the World, discusses the problem with Pablo Shapira of Rewilding Spain, an organisation combating wildfires in central Spain.

26
00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:20.000
One of the reasons for this is that the forests have been left to grow on checks, as the simply aren't enough animals to feed on all the trees,

27
00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:26.000
bushes and grass. And the more dense this vegetation is, the more likely it is to catch fire.

28
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:31.000
What we've had before in our ecosystems here in Europe, is that we had big raises.

29
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:38.000
We had the bison, we had autos, we had wildfires. And now they are gone from the ecosystem because of extinction, the mystication.

30
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:47.000
Many European forests have grown unchecked. If something is left unchecked, nobody controls it or prevents it from increasing.

31
00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:53.000
The problem is that when trees, grass and vegetation are left to grow, they're more likely to catch fire.

32
00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:59.000
Hundreds of years ago, animals known as grazers, with simply the eaten this vegetation up.

33
00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:08.000
To graze, means to eat grass and other wild plants, and grazers are the animals, including horses, cows and goats which do this.

34
00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:14.000
In English, you can also say a person is grazing if they continually eat snacks or little bites of food.

35
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:31.000
But in modern times, numbers of grazing animals have declined sharply because of extinction, when a species of animal, the dinosaurs, for example, no longer exist, and domestication, when wild animals are controlled by humans to work or for food.

36
00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:43.000
And, as numbers of grazing wild animals decrease, forest and grasslands continue to grow unchecked, leading to the large wildfires which now regularly happen in Spain.

37
00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:53.000
And that's where our four-legged friends, the cows, come to the rescue. Supported by re-wilding Spain, Pablo has reintroduced herds of Toros.

38
00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:02.000
These species of cows similar to the now extinct wild orrox, the ancestor of the modern domestic cow into the forest of central Spain.

39
00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:08.000
Here's reporter Craig Langran again for BBC World Service Program, people fixing the world.

40
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:18.000
Along with the cows, voracious appetite, they trample in the vegetation, and it's that trampling that helps to open up the forest, so it's not so densely packed full of flammable vegetation.

41
00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:24.000
Toros eat everything from grass and leaves to tree branches and bark.

42
00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:29.000
Craig says the cows are voracious, or very eager for lots of food.

43
00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:39.000
What's more, by wandering freely around the forest, they trampled down dead trees, reducing the amounts of flammable meaning easily burnt vegetation.

44
00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:46.000
They don't wear firemen's helmets, but these four-legged firefighting friends are really coming to the rescue in Spain.

45
00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:50.000
Okay, Neil, isn't it time to reveal the answer to your question?

46
00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:55.000
Yes, I asked you what proportion of wildfires are caused by people.

47
00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:59.000
And I said three out of five, was I right?

48
00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:07.000
I'm afraid you're wrong, Beth. The answer was C, according to the Natural History Museum of Utah, four out of every five wildfires are man-made.

49
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:13.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned from this program, starting with the adjective unchecked.

50
00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:18.000
If something harmful is left unchecked, nobody controls it or prevents it from growing.

51
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:24.000
So, graze means to eat grass and vegetation. Grazers are animals like cows which do this.

52
00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:29.000
An a person who grazes continually eats little bites of food.

53
00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:37.000
Extinction is when an animal species no longer exists. The dinosaurs and the wild or rocks are two examples of extinct animals.

54
00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:44.000
Domestication is when wild animals become controlled by humans for work, food, or as pets.

55
00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:49.000
The adjective voracious means very eager for something, especially a lot of food.

56
00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:55.000
And finally, if something is flammable, it easily burns or catches fire.

57
00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Once again, our six minutes are up. If you enjoy this program, why not check out the accompanying worksheet and quiz both available at BBCLearningEnglish.com.

58
00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:06.000
Goodbye.

59
00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:07.000
Goodbye for now.
